I don&#x27;t know if Boost&#x27;s intrustive containers are necessarily quite the same as an internal linked list. std::list<T> is internal but not intrustive; the difference between the three is something like…<p>external:<p><pre><code>    class Node<T> {
        Node *next;
        T *item;
    }
</code></pre>
internal:<p><pre><code>    class Node<T> {
        Node *next;
        T item;
    }
</code></pre>
intrusive:<p><pre><code>    typedef T Node<T>;
    class <T> {
        Node *next;
        // members of T
    };
</code></pre>
(Though I suppose you could consider intrusive a type of internal linked list, and the middle representation is then also a type of internal linked list (&quot;non-intrusive&quot;?).)<p>The intrusive one allows the linked list to avoid memory allocations, and hold objects that are not copy- or move-able. The Boost page has a good table on the differences[1].<p>I&#x27;m actually not sure how much I agree w/ the codeofhorror article. They present the difference between a std::list holding raw pointers and an intrusive list with the title &quot;Avoiding Game Crashes…&quot;; if you want to avoid crashes, std::list<T> or std::list<std::unique_ptr<T>> (or even a shared_ptr, if appropriate); Of course std::list<T*> is error prone!<p>[1]: <a href="http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_55_0/doc/html/intrusive/intrusive_vs_nontrusive.html#intrusive.intrusive_vs_nontrusive.properties_of_intrusive" rel="nofollow">http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_55_0/doc/html/intrusive/intr...</a>
